      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A mother from a rural area brings her 4-day-old baby to the clinic for vaccination. As the attending physician, you notice abnormalities in the child&#39;s appearance as depicted in the provided image, prompting a thorough examination. The neonate exhibits overlapping fingers, an elongated occiput, curved feet, hypoplastic nails, and cleft lip and palate. Given these findings, you suspect a chromosomal anomaly and recommend an echocardiography, which reveals a ventricular septal defect. Based on the neonate&#39;s history, clinical presentation and echo findings, what is the most likely diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/16/picture5.jpg\" style=\"height:181px; width:400px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
