      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 24-year-old mother, Mala, recently gave birth to a neonate presenting with epicanthal folds, low-set ears, a small nose, and a protruding tongue. Additionally, Brushfield spots were observed in the eyes. Echocardiography revealed endocardial cushion defects. Upon feeding, the neonate vomited milk with a bilious tinge, leading to a suspicion of duodenal atresia alongside the clinical suspicion of Down syndrome. Considering these findings, what is the most common genetic cause of this syndrome?</span></span></span></p>",
