        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) Maternal meiotic non- dysjunction </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The clinical features mentioned are <strong>because of the trisomy 21, It is the mc trisomy</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Cytogenetics</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: trisomy 21 is due to</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Maternal meiotic non-dysjunction (94%)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Robertsonian translocation-t(21;21) and t(14;21) (5%)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Mosaicism (1%)</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Clinical features:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Craniofacial-flat face, upward slanted palpebral fissures, epicanthal folds, speckled iris (brushfield spots), small nose and flat nasal bridge.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">CVS defects-endocardial cushion defects (40-50%), VSD, ASD, patent ductus arteriosus.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Musculoskeletal-joint hyper flexibility, short neck, short metacarpal and phalanges, wide gap between 1<sup>st</sup> and 2<sup>nd</sup> toe.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Gastrointestinal-duodenal atresia (mc), annular pancreases, tracheoesophageal fistula.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:48px; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Germline mosaicism</strong>: This occurs when <strong>some of the body&#39;s cells have a different genetic makeup from the rest</strong>, which can lead to genetic conditions but it is only responsible for only 1% cases of Down syndrome (least common).</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:48px; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Paternal meiotic nondisjunction</strong>: </span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Paternal meiotic is not evident in case of down syndrome</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Translocation</strong>: Down syndrome can also result from a <strong>Robertsonian translocation</strong>, where a <strong>significant portion of chromosome 21 is attached to another chromosome</strong>, typically chromosome 14. However, this accounts for least common causes for </span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">down syndrome.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective</span></u></strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: </span></u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Remember </strong>- <strong>Maternal meiotic nondisjunction </strong>is the <strong>most common cause of Down Syndrome</strong>. It also <strong>aims to highlight the association between Down and various congenital anomalies</strong>, such as <strong>duodenal atresia </strong>and <strong>cardiac defects</strong>, which require prompt recognition and management in affected neonates.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:</span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No 610-615.</span></span></strong></p>",
